judge and prophet of the greatest historical importance, who established the Hebrew monarchy, anointing as king both Saul and, later, David. In the Authorized Version two books of the Old Testament are named after him, although in Roman Catholic and Orthodox versions of the Bible they are known as the first and second Book of Kings. The story of Samuel being called by God while still a child serving in the house of Eli the priest (1 Samuel 3) is of great vividness and has moved countless generations. In England and America the name was particularly popular among the 16th-century Puritans and among Nonconformists from the 17th to the 19th century. It became fashionable again in the 1990s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":28,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":59,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Samuel Cox was born about 1231, in Gloucestershire, England, his father, Thomas Joel Cox, was 32 and his mother, Nellie May Angell, was 32. He married Mrs. Cox about 1250, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1300, in England, at the age of 70."},"et":{"about 1231–1300":"umbes 1231–1300","1231–1300":"1231–1300","–Female":"Surnud","1251–1312":"1251–1312","1200–1275":"1200–1275","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1275":"1275","1231":"1231","1251":"1251","about 1231":"umbes 1231","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1290":"1290","England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Glo